text:
The Towers of Hanoi puzzle consists of three rods and n disks of differing sizes stacked in decreasing order on one rod. The objective is to move the entire stack to another rod, obeying two rules: only one disk may move at a time, and a larger disk cannot rest atop a smaller one. The recursive solution exploits self-similarity. To move n disks from rod A to rod C using auxiliary rod B, first move n-1 disks from A to B. Then move the largest disk from A to C. Finally, move the n-1 disks from B to C. The base case occurs when n equals zero, requiring no action. In C, this translates to:

void hanoi(int n, char from, char aux, char to) {
    if (n == 0) return;
    hanoi(n - 1, from, to, aux);
    printf("Move disk %d from %c to %c\n", n, from, to);
    hanoi(n - 1, aux, from, to);
}

The recurrence relation T(n) = 2T(n-1) + 1 solves to T(n) = 2^n - 1, which is provably optimal.
